Adult female. Unmounted material.
“Slightly longer than wide, flat, the center usually slightly elevated, with faint radiating ridges around the margin, dirty pale brown, appearing as if covered with a thin film of dust; ..” (
Morrison 1921: 662
). Morrison’s description probably was based on dried specimens and thus differs in body colour from live specimens photographed from two regions in Borneo. Live adult females varied from pale yellowish-white to pale pink or dark pink (
Fig. 2F
), depending on age, with the dorsal wax appearing granular due to being composed of small irregularly shaped pieces, and the marginal stigmatic areas were often distinct due to accumulation of white wax.

